			<tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				I have the utmost respect for Asimov -- he was one of 2 or 3 men who got science fiction from pulp paperbacks in the 40s and 50s into mass market novels and movies in the 60s and 70s.  He wrote over 500 books -- more of them non-fiction than fiction.  His doctorate is in biochemistry from Columbia U. and the research and science behind his stories is impeccable.  "I, Robot" was a collection of short stories written in the 50s in which he developed the three Laws of Robotics:
<br />

<br />
1. A robot may not harm a human being or through inaction allow a human being to come to harm.
<br />

<br />
2. A robot must obey the orders of a human being except where it would conflict with the first law.
<br />

<br />
3. A robot must preserve its own existence except where it would conflict with the first or second laws.
<br />

<br />
He later added a "Zero-eth" law stating that a robot cannot harm humanity as a whole, or through inaction allow humanity to come to harm.  These laws, including the Zero-eth, were incorporated into Data's programming in Star Trek: Next Generation and have been applied by countless SF writers in the past half century.  I fear the movie is going to take a few salient background points from the books and turn them into a Terminator-like explosion festival, something Asimov would have abhorred.  One of the heroes of "I, Robot" was a woman given credit for much of the development of the robots' positronic brain.  Asimov was way ahead of the rest of society by suggesting in the 50s that a female scientist could revolutionize the world in that way.  Dr. Asimov was my first hero as a writer and his book "Building Blocks of the Universe" taught me to understand the periodic table when I was in junior high.  I miss him.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
		</table>
		</td>
